******
[2]
Date: 29 Jan 2011
Source: Yonhap via Korea Joongang Daily [summarised, edited]
<http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2931627>


Korea's imports of beef and pork have jumped this month [January 2011]
amid a massive slaughter of cattle and pigs caused by the spreading
FMD, the Korea Customs Service said yesterday [Fri 28 Jan 2011].

Korea imported 24 513 tons of beef during the 1st 21 days of this
month [January 2011], up 22.7 percent from the same period a month
earlier. Pork imports also jumped 31.1 percent to 26 625 tons.

Prices per-kilogram of beef and pork also jumped 25.1 percent and 16.7
percent this month [January 2011] compared with the same period a year
ago.

Korea has culled around 2.6 million livestock since the outbreak of
the highly contagious disease in late November [2010]. The disease has
spread almost across the entire nation now despite the government's
stepped-up quarantine efforts.

Prices of pork and other meats soared in the domestic market, making
it more expensive for people to prepare meals for family gatherings
during the Lunar New Year holiday early next week.

As part of stabilizing meat prices, the finance ministry said Tuesday
[25 Jan 2011] that it will cut import tariffs on 60 000 tons of pork
from the current 25 percent to zero until the end of June 2011. Pork
is cheaper than beef and popular especially among working-class people.

The move is in line with ongoing government anti-inflation efforts and
is also aimed at easing price hikes amid worries that demand for the
meat is expected to spike ahead of the upcoming holiday.

In an earlier meeting to discuss anti-inflation measures, Vice Finance
Minister Yim Jong-yong said that the government will take "every
possible measure" to stabilize soaring pork prices as part of efforts
to ease the suffering of working-class people.

"We take the supply shortage of pork caused by FMD seriously," Yim
said at the meeting with other policymakers. "We will respond actively
[with market situations] by pursuing every possible measure, including
expanding the tariff quota [on pork]."

He added that the government will work hard to stabilize prices of key
agricultural and fishery goods.

