******
[3]
Date: Sat 29 Jan 2011
Source: Canada.com [edited]
<http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=4190119&sponsor=>


Canada will ship more pork to South Korea due to an outbreak of FMD
that has ravaged South Korea's pig herds, Agriculture Minister Gerry
Ritz said on Friday [28 Jan 2011].

South Korea's government said it may raise a quota for tariff-free
pork imports to help boost local supplies.

Pork prices spiked to record levels in Asia's 4th-largest economy
after it culled nearly 30 percent of its hog population to stop the
spread of the disease among livestock.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Since the start of the FMD epizootic in South Korea, there have been
repeated statements explaining the application of the disease-control
policy "no vaccination, stamping out with culling of contiguous
animals" by the need to prevent damage to the country's exports of
animals and their products in case S. Korea's status of "FMD-free
without vaccination" is lost.

We have attempted to obtain data on S. Korea's exports in recent
years, during which Korea maintained the status of an "FMD-free
without vaccination" country. With the kind assistance of a subscriber
to whom we are very grateful, the following (most recent available)
information, pertaining to 2008 and 2009, has been obtained.

1. Live animals (cattle, sheep, goats, pigs): export negligible or nil
during both 2008 and 2009.

2. Pork: 2008 - total export (to 22 countries) of 10 405 325 kg for
the value of USD 17 716 376. The main buyers were Russia, Philippines,
Thailand and China (respectively USD 9 197 402, 4 919 435, 1 792 165
and 1 279 380 each).

2009 - total export (to 20 countries) of 12 513 335.5 kg for the value
of USD 11 624 578. The main buyers were Philippines (USD 6 869 109)
and Thailand (USD 3 163 573).

3. Beef: 2008 - total export of 254 961.9 kg for the value of USD 748 809.

2009 - total export of 2 526 305.9 kg for the value of USD 7 969 287.
The main buyers were China (4 417 838), Viet Nam (USD 1 734 752) and
USA (USD 1 054 040).

S. Korea has traditionally been predominantly an importer, not
exporter of animals and their products. - Mod.AS]
